<module>
    <h>determiners</h>
    <p>There are two main classes of determiner – <ul>
            <li>forms of the <a href="?xx=nouns/definite_article">definite article</a> – <g>an</g>,
                    <g>am</g>, <g>a’</g>, <g>na</g>, <g>nan</g>, <g>nam</g></li>
            <li>the possessive determiners – <g>mo</g>, <g>do</g>, <g>a</g>, <g>ar</g>, <g>bhur</g>,
                    <g>an</g>/<g>am</g></li>
            <!--<li><a href="?gd=gach">gach</a>
                <en>each, every, all</en></li>-->
        </ul>
    </p>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section>
            <h>specifier</h>
            <p>A determiner is used as the pre-specifier of a <a href="?xx=nouns/common_nouns"
                    >common noun</a>.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>A bheil <m>an cù</m> aig <m>an dorus</m>?</gd>
                        <tr>Is the dog at the door?</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 11</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>


